properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 171
properties.hasText: Protect buffers and floodplain rivers, as this will benefit estuaries by reducing pollutant input and reducing drastic changes in freshwater input.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 172
properties.hasText: Protect inland tidal freshwater wetlands, which will become extensive estuarine communities in the future, and allow the barrier islands to migrate and new inlets to form.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 173
properties.hasText: Protect habitats in large enough patches to sustain priority species, reconnect fragmented habitats, restore habitats that have been lost or converted, enhance the function and structure of habitats that have been degraded, and manage habitats for priority species (ACJV 2004).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 174
properties.hasText: Work with partners (e.g., NC Coastal Federation, Audubon NC, TNC, Ducks Unlimited) to leverage funding programs such as the North American Wetlands Conservation Act that target conservation of coastal wetlands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 175
properties.hasText: Implement conservation measures outlined in the Albemarle–Pamlico National Estuary Partnership (see http://portal.ncdenr.org/web/apnep).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 193
properties.hasText: Initiate partnerships with the Natural Resources Conservation Service to begin cane restoration projects and research.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 194
properties.hasText: Continue cooperative efforts with colonial waterbird (wading bird) working groups and follow future management recommendations from the North American Waterbird Management Plan (Kushlan et al. 2002).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 195
properties.hasText: Work to develop eight patches of forested wetlands at least 10,000 acres in size throughout the South [[Atlantic Coastal Plain]], as called for in the South [[Atlantic Coastal Plain]] Partners in Flight Bird Conservation Plan (Hunter et al. 2001b).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 229
properties.hasText: Make an attempt to protect waterbird nesting colonies. Continue cooperative efforts with colonial waterbird (wading bird) working groups and follow future management recommendations from the North American Waterbird Management Plan (Kushlan et al. 2002).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 230
properties.hasText: Make efforts to retain old growth floodplain forest for chimney swifts, bats, and herpetofauna.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 231
properties.hasText: Work to develop eight patches of forested wetlands at least 10,000 acres in size throughout the South [[Atlantic Coastal Plain]], as called for in the South [[Atlantic Coastal Plain]] Partners in Flight Bird Conservation Plan (Hunter et al. 2000b).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 233
properties.hasText: Further expand the Forest Landbird Legacy Program (a cooperative effort between the Commission, the US Fish and Wildlife Service [USFWS], and the Natural Resources Conservation Service) to influence habitat for birds and other wildlife in mature floodplain forest through canopy gap management and other options.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 234
properties.hasText: Concentrate conservation efforts on the Pee Dee and Dan River basins, as they contain some of the larger tracts of intact floodplain forest left in the [[Piedmont]] and offer some of the best opportunities for large-scale habitat conservation.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 235
properties.hasText: Pursue land acquisition and easements through cooperation with land trusts with an effort to increase the width of riparian buffers and create larger patches of connected habitat. Priority should be given to brownwater bottomlands, as these are the most species-rich and are more susceptible to clearcutting and other timber harvest than cypress-gum swamps (i.e., wetter sites) (NCWRC 2005).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 236
properties.hasText: Wherever possible, maintenance or restoration of floodplain forest connectivity should be pursued; floodplain forest are important distribution and dispersal corridors for many species (Bailey et al. 2004 in NCWRC 2005).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 277
properties.hasText: Priorities for protection include colonial waterbird nesting sites, eagle nesting sites, [[Wood Stork]] foraging areas, and important [[Black Rail]] habitat once it is better identified. Adjacent nesting habitat for snakes and turtles should also be protected.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 278
properties.hasText: Acquisition of freshwater tidal marsh habitat in the Currituck Sound area is important.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 286
properties.hasText: Collaborate with partners to develop a management plan for high-elevation communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 303
properties.hasText: Protect from trampling to allow the species pool to expand through suitable habitat, producing larger, more robust populations that would be better able to survive climate-related changes.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 304
properties.hasText: Ensure that all existing high-elevation rock outcrops are high priorities for conservation action, as they are extremely rare, have a very restricted range, and are subject to extreme environmental conditions.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 305
properties.hasText: Close sensitive areas at certain times (e.g., during Timber Rattlesnake emergence or [[Peregrine Falcon]] nesting) or permanently to stop direct trampling, loss of habitat to recreation developments, trails, vistas, etc., and indirect human impacts (disturbance).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 316
properties.hasText: Increase buffer widths to mitigate impacts from pollution into river systems and to maintain habitatat the edge of these aquatic communities that will provide cover and foraging areas for many wildlife species using riverine habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 317
properties.hasText: Pursue land acquisition and easements through cooperation with land trusts in an effort to increase the width of riparian buffers and create larger patches of connected habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 330
properties.hasText: Protect remaining examples and surrounding forests. Sites should be protected from human disturbance, including locations that are already protected through conservation measures. This may be through closure during particular times of the year or permanently prohibiting use of the site.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 331
properties.hasText: Given the relative rarity of low-elevation rock outcrops across the state, measures need to be taken to conserve as much of this habitat as possible. This includes preservation measures, as well as conservation/management measures to ensure that species that rely upon these outcrops continue to be afforded the desired variety of habitat conditions into the future.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 340
properties.hasText: Close sites to stop direct (trampling, loss of habitat to recreation developments such as trails, vistas, etc.) and indirect (disturbance) human impacts.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 341
properties.hasText: Use easements and land acquisition to protect from long-term impacts such as housing development.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 357
properties.hasText: Make remaining coastal maritime habitats a priority for land acquisition efforts. Though coastal uplands are essentially the most costly areas to acquire in the state, it is essential to acquire remaining undeveloped maritime forests, both on barrier islands and on the mainland.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 358
properties.hasText: Pursue reestablishment of maritime forest habitats, including initiation of prescribed burning of appropriate maritime habitats, where possible.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 380
properties.hasText: Continue coordination with waterbird working groups such as the North Carolina Waterbird Committee, the [[Piping Plover]] Recovery Team, the [[American Oystercatcher]] Working Group, and the [[Royal Tern]] Working Group.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 381
properties.hasText: Implement future recommendations from the North American Waterbird Conservation Plan (Kushlan et al. 2002).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 391
properties.hasText: Create cooperative programs with non-industrial foresters that promote and increase silvicultural practices (e.g., canopy gap management, longer rotations, introduction of fire), as this could benefit birds of conservation concern as well as small mammals, bats, reptiles, and amphibians.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 392
properties.hasText: Give high priority to protecting movement corridors that allow dispersal between habitat blocks, especially as development and roadways fragment the few remaining large tracts of habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 393
properties.hasText: Give priority to restoring connections that are lost due to construction of four-lane highways and other roads that create near-impassible barriers for all animals except those capable of flight.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 394
properties.hasText: Ensure that conservation actions include land acquisition, easements, and protection to promote remaining large, unfragmented tracts as well as management to maintain and reestablish mesic forest. This is a relatively rare forest type and great effort should be made to protect mesic forests and their species assemblages. Conservation of larger natural areas that include adjacent communities will lead to greater viability for all communities present.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 421
properties.hasText: Work with partners like Prescribed Fire Council and the Fire Learning Network to reinstate prescribed burning, which is perhaps the most important action that can make oak forests better able to withstand climate change.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 422
properties.hasText: Create wildlife passages along highways and protect undeveloped connections.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 423
properties.hasText: Identify and protect strategically important areas.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 438
properties.hasText: Site protection and protection of surrounding areas through land acquisition or easements and cooperation with land trusts are urgently needed, as large acreages (>500 acres) are frequently clearcut all at once for agriculture, pine conversion, or development.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 439
properties.hasText: Restoration efforts may be possible in some cases through partnerships with land trusts, the Nature Conservancy, and state and federal agencies.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 453
properties.hasText: Make particular effort to protect examples at the higher elevations, where the community is likely to persist and where the seed source for migration to higher elevations will primarily come from.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 454
properties.hasText: Protect the current habitat and connectivity of isolated patches through conservation ownership acquisition or easement.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 455
properties.hasText: Increase connectivity among habitat patches, both through acquisition or management of adjacent stands. Preservation of large tracts of minimally disturbed older forests may be key to maintaining forest litter amphibian populations.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 469
properties.hasText: Use landowner incentives to promote extending rotation lengths for timber.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 470
properties.hasText: Give a high priority to protecting movement corridors that allow dispersal between habitat blocks, especially as development and roadways fragment the few remaining large tracts of habitat. Maintaining and restoring connections between habitat blocks is critical, not only for allowing adjustments in range in response to climate change, but to maintain population resilience and adaptability more generally.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 471
properties.hasText: Give priority to restoring connections that are lost due to construction of four-lane highways and other roads that create nearly impassible barriers for all animals except those capable of flight.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 472
properties.hasText: Direct county and state-level land use planning to minimize development within large, unfragmented tracts of forests. This would be most appropriate and effective in the regions that are, as yet, not heavily developed, including Montgomery, Stanly, Randolph and Richmond counties in the southern [[Piedmont]], and the northern tier counties of Surry, Stokes, Rockingham, Caswell, Person, and Granville.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 473
properties.hasText: Concentrate planning for future infrastructure (roads, water lines, etc.) closer to existing development and avoid dissecting larger tracks of unfragmented forest.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 474
properties.hasText: Make attempts to provide large core areas of forest and to connect isolated patches of forests. Cooper (2000) recommends that core areas be at least 16,000 acres in size to produce viable populations of forest-interior birds, like [[Scarlet Tanager]]. Large core areas will be important for reptiles like Eastern Box Turtle and Timber Rattlesnake, which suffer high mortality when crossing roads.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 483
properties.hasText: Focus land acquisition on consolidating these areas into larger holdings so that they may be managed through fire.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 484
properties.hasText: Discern and offer increased protection to specialized pocosin types. Though extensive amounts of pocosin lands are already protected, some require more protection, such as Carolina bays (Bladen Lakes area) and white cedar stands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 500
properties.hasText: Limit lakeshoredevelopment at sites where there is no protected buffer land.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 501
properties.hasText: Acquire lakeshorebuffer lands (as was done at Jordan and Falls reservoirs) to exclude development.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 502
properties.hasText: Implement conservation strategies where appropriate to protect downstream reaches of relic dams where there are known populations of priority mussel species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 53
properties.hasText: Land use planning and zoning laws are needed to guide development, land clearing activities, and hydrology alterations within floodplains. Planning such as this may for example route highways and other corridors that cross floodplains as closely as possible to existing corridors to avoid fragmenting an extensive corridor of forest.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 530
properties.hasText: Protect existing large blocks of habitat and restoreconnections between these blocks in order to benefit the species in this group and to enhance the viability of the state's native biodiversity overall.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 531
properties.hasText: Protect smaller tracts that are situated between blocks so they can function as a corridor between conservation sites.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 532
properties.hasText: In the Coastal Plain, give a high priority to protecting movement corridors that allow inland migration away from inundating areas along the sounds and seacoast.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 533
properties.hasText: Over the state as a whole, give a high priority to restoring connections that are lost due to construction of four-lane highways and other roads that create near-impassible barriers for all animals except those capable of flight.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 54
properties.hasText: Undertake immediate and continuing efforts to limit water quality deterioration from point sources of pollution as well as nonpoint sources. In general, the most critical conservation actions necessary to sustain populations of riverine habitat species involve protection of water quality and aquatic habitats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 548
properties.hasText: Eliminate or minimize negative effects of future development in state and federal government holdings (state and federal parks, [[USDA Forest Service

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 549
properties.hasText: Acquire additional acreage of spruce–fir habitat through purchase, conservation easement, or other perpetual management agreements (particularly in the Plott Balsams and Black/Craggy Mountains).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 55
properties.hasText: Protect floodplains and riparian wetlands from development or land uses that interfere with flood control or floodwater attenuation. Changes in flood patterns (frequency and duration) and flooded lands may periodically require updating flood maps to ensure protection of life and property (Band and Salvesen, 2009).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 56
properties.hasText: Preserve forests and open space, farm land, rural landscapes, and park lands. Manage open lands and plant trees and vegetation in urban areas to aid in carbon sequestration.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 57
properties.hasText: Plant riparian areas with vegetation with a broad elevational range within a particular watershed and with broad hydrologic tolerance to promote resiliency from climate change.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 58
properties.hasText: Use easements and value taxation, and fee simple purchase for land conservation or preservation.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 584
properties.hasText: Protect existing large blocks of habitat and restore connections between these blocks, as this will not only benefit the species in this group, but will enhance the viability of the state's native biodiversity overall.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 588
properties.hasText: Preserve riparian buffers and floodplains, especially where clearcutting near wetlands causes higher solar radiation and an increase in probability of wetlands drying out.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 589
properties.hasText: Place a high priority on protecting wetlands and adjacent uplands through acquisition or easement.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 59
properties.hasText: Promote efforts to control stormwater management and point source pollution.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 600
properties.hasText: Make every effort to maintain continuous gradients between wetland and upland sites; roads, agriculture, or forestry operations between complimentary sites may render them ineffective at supporting amphibian and reptile populations (Bailey et al. 2004; NCWRC 2005).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 601
properties.hasText: Provide for habitat connectivity between nearby upland pools and other wetlands or surface waters.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 602
properties.hasText: Place high priority on protecting wetlands and adjacent uplands through acquisition or easement.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 606
properties.hasText: Actively pursue acquisition of conservation ownership of mountain bogs in concert with state and federal agency partners as well as private conservation partners.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 75
properties.hasText: Acquire cave habitat through purchase, conservation easement, or other perpetual management agreements (potential for partnerships with NC Natural Heritage Program, The Nature Conservancy).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 76
properties.hasText: Develop plans to protect caves where roosting bats or other cave resources are at risk from human intrusion.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 88
properties.hasText: Plant riparian areas with native vegetation with a broad elevationalrange within a particular watershed and with broad hydrologic tolerance to promote resilience from climate change.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 93
properties.hasText: Promote efforts to control stormwater management point source pollution.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 102
properties.hasText: With the vast majority of cove hardwood habitat in mid-successional stages, efforts should be directed toward increasing older age classes of cove hardwoods by both lengthening harvest rotation recommendations for timberland owners, and exploring whether we can mimic old growth gap dynamic conditions through selective harvesting techniques in midto late-successional cove hardwood stands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 103
properties.hasText: Protect cove forests from severe wildfire during drought periods to prevent catastrophic disturbance. In more favorable periods, prescribed burning of surrounding landscapes would help reduce the risk of controllable wildfire, as well as benefitting the upland communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 113
properties.hasText: Determine impacts of prescribed fire on these communities and the resulting effects on wildlife communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 114
properties.hasText: Develop logistically and economically effective control strategies for controlling outbreaks of the most damaging insect pests and diseases.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 115
properties.hasText: Regulate human activities on steep slopes that may cause excessive erosion or mud slides, and develop and implement BMPs to mitigate erosion.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 123
properties.hasText: Where possible, allow fire to burn through transition zones to maintain these sites instead of plowing fire lines through them.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 124
properties.hasText: Suppress Fire Ant colonies—particularly where multi-queen colonies have developed—in all protected natural areas.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 125
properties.hasText: Restore landscape integrity to protect insect populations associated with Longleaf Pine habitats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 126
properties.hasText: Evaluate sustainable forestry criteria established by European countries that use woody biomass for fuel to generate preliminary guidelines for biomass production in North Carolina (Buford and Neary 2010 in DeWan et al. 2010).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 127
properties.hasText: Develop strategies for pine straw raking that minimizes impacts to understory habitat structure.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 141
properties.hasText: Planning and locating wastewater treatment facilities to areas above sea level will minimize or eliminate risks (APNEP 2012).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 142
properties.hasText: Restore areas capable of supporting SAVs. This will require study of effective restoration techniques, bathymetric mapping, water quality monitoring, and other efforts (APNEP 2012).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 143
properties.hasText: Develop and refine ecological flow requirements for each major river (APNEP 2012) that drains to estuarine waters.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 144
properties.hasText: Reduce potential water pollution by protecting critical buffer areas of upstream drainages, sound planning, adopting low-impact development (LID) criteria, and other best practices.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 145
properties.hasText: Establish contaminant management strategies for waters not meeting water quality standards. Strategies that addresspathogens, toxics, and nutrients are needed, not just the traditional total maximum daily load (TMDL) plans which primarily manage industrial point sources and municipal stormwater (APNEP 2012).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 146
properties.hasText: Where practical, restore marsh habitatby filling drainage ditches and install tide gates in agricultural fields so that sea water does not flow inland through them (DeWan et al. 2010).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 147
properties.hasText: Consider closing fisheries for declining species during the spawning season.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 164
properties.hasText: Allow barrier islands to migrate, as it increases their chance of survival and reduces the chance of sudden and drastic changes in tidal regime in the estuaries.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 165
properties.hasText: Where practical, restore marsh habitat by filling drainage ditches and installing ditch plugs and water control structures. Ditches may accelerate erosion and the effects of rising sea level such as saltwater intrusion.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 166
properties.hasText: Protect suitable nesting habitat for sea turtles and beach-nesting birds to maintain robust populations as disturbance and sea level rise issues mount.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 167
properties.hasText: Continue working with the US Army Corps of Engineers and others to direct dredged material or conduct other management actions to refurbish waterbird nesting islands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 168
properties.hasText: Continue coordination with the NC Division of Marine Fisheries to minimize bycatch of protected/priority species in fishing gear.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 104
properties.hasText: Add to our base of conservation ownership for future generations of the wildlife species associated with the habitat, as well as the use and enjoyment of them by future generations of North Carolinians.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 105
properties.hasText: Protect examples in the most sheltered sites, and those that serve as landscape connections to other patches.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 116
properties.hasText: Continue to support partnerships like the [[Southern Blue Ridge]] Fire Learning Network and the North Carolina Prescribed Fire Council to expand efforts at restoring disturbance regimes.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 117
properties.hasText: Identify the best remaining examples of this habitat in the Mountains and western [[Piedmont]] and then to pursue easements or acquisition. The efforts of land trusts and government agencies should be coordinated to target the highest priority sites.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 118
properties.hasText: Use land use planning to minimize development within large, unfragmented tracts of all woodland types in the western [[Piedmont]].

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 128
properties.hasText: Work cooperatively with other agencies to define sustainable forestry criteria for biomass production.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 129
properties.hasText: Provide landowners with the option to purchase longleaf seedlings that stay in the grass stage longer. This will allow the trees to better establish their root systems in the hurricane zone, and will also provide a longer period of high-quality early successional habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 130
properties.hasText: Give high priority to protecting and expanding the few remaining examples regardless of climate change. Because these systems are likely to withstand the stresses of changing climate well, restoring more of them in the near future would produce more resilient natural landscapes.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 148
properties.hasText: Facilitate the development of state and local policies that support the use of LID practices to reduce runoff (APNEP 2012).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 149
properties.hasText: Facilitate the use of BMPs on agricultural and silvicultural lands (APNEP 2012).Runoff can carry sediments, nitrogen, phosphorus, pesticides, and other substances into the sounds.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 15
properties.hasText: Focus habitatprotection measures on utilizing existing regulatory frameworks to protect both the habitatand these species (e.g., state and federal endangered species laws, wetland protection laws, etc.).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 150
properties.hasText: Facilitate protection of designated anadromous fish spawning areas and inland primary nursery areas from marina impacts (APNEP 2012).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 151
properties.hasText: Establish marsh habitats in cleared areas that are likely to become wetlands in the future due to inundation or frequent flooding.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 152
properties.hasText: Protect conservation corridors that run from shorelines inland to facilitate habitat migration (DeWan et al. 2010).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 153
properties.hasText: Establish oyster reefs and SAV beds offshore to help buffer shorelines (DeWan et al. 2010; Pearsall and Poulter 2005).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 154
properties.hasText: Consider establishing marine reserves to provide refuge from fishing pressure, facilitate adult migration patterns and larval dispersal pathways, and support fisheries restoration efforts (DiBacco et al. 2006).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 16
properties.hasText: Fully utilize government conservation programs and incentives (e.g., Farm Bill programs) and partnerships with private landowners to stem the conversion of suitable bogs to other uses.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 17
properties.hasText: Actively pursue conservation ownership through acquisition of mountain bogs in concert with state and federal agency partners (e.g., US Fish and Wildlife Service [USFWS], US Forest Service, National Parks Service, Natural Resources Conservation Service, NC Division of Parks and Recreation, NC Natural Heritage Program, local governments, etc.) as well as private conservation partners (e.g., The Nature Conservancy,land trusts).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Conservation Programs And Partnerships Priority 170
properties.hasText: Protect tidal freshwater wetlands in rivers and upper sounds, some of which will become the extensive estuarine communities in the future. Salt and brackish marshes will benefit from this.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 169
properties.hasText: Control or minimize the amount of large gull depredation on other beach-nesting birds. These large gulls did not nest in the state until recent decades but are now greatly increasing in number and are causing more pressure on beach-nesting bird populations.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 184
properties.hasText: Explore techniques for restoration of tidal swamp forest and wetlands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 189
properties.hasText: Wherever possible, maintain or restore floodplain forest connectivity, as floodplain forests are important distribution and dispersal corridors for many species (Bailey et al. 2004). This would benefit floodplain forest species such as the [[Northern Parula]], Yellow-Throated Warbler, [[Prothonotary Warbler]], [[Wood Thrush]], [[Swainson's Warbler]], and [[Acadian Flycatcher]], as well as amphibians, Timber Rattlesnakes, and forest bats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 190
properties.hasText: Ensure floodplain buffers of 300 to 600 feet in as many areas as possible. Where possible, forest patches should be connected along river systems to provide connectivity.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 223
properties.hasText: Make efforts to retain old growth floodplain forest (for [[Chimney Swift]]s, bats, and herpetofauna).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 224
properties.hasText: Ensure floodplain buffers of 300 to 600 feet in as many areas as possible. This would benefit floodplain forest species such as the [[Northern Parula]], [[Swallow-tailed Kite]], [[Mississippi Kite]], [[Prothonotary Warbler]], [[Wood Thrush]], Swainson's and Cerulean warblers, and [[Acadian Flycatcher]], as well as amphibians, Timber Rattlesnakes, and forest bats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 225
properties.hasText: Restore natural hydrology where dams have altered hydrology, such as on the Roanoke River.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 226
properties.hasText: Work with partners to institute more natural water release regimes from dams.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 228
properties.hasText: Floodplain buffers of 300 to 600 feet provide the most benefit for species such as [[Northern Parula]], [[Yellow-throated Warbler]], [[Prothonotary Warbler]], [[Wood Thrush]], [[Swainson's Warbler]], [[Worm-eating Warbler]], and [[Acadian Flycatcher]], as well as amphibians, snakes, and forest bats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 273
properties.hasText: Explore techniques for restoring tidal swamp forest and wetlands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 274
properties.hasText: Consider planting bald cypress to create the next shoreline as sea level rises and blocking ditches to slow saltwater flow into the interior of freshwater tidal marsh as a measure to reduce erosion and buy time for habitat migration inland.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 275
properties.hasText: Use prescribed fire to burn portions of tidal freshwater marshes to eliminate or set-back competing woody species. Mechanical cutting of woody vegetation may be more feasible in wetter areas that cannot be reached by fire.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 276
properties.hasText: The use of bulkheads should be discouraged when other possibilities are available.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 284
properties.hasText: Initiate a prescribed fire regime to control invasive plants and prevent habitat conversion.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 285
properties.hasText: Control invasive species and protect or restore areas, as this is critical to protect these habitats against threats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 292
properties.hasText: Use stormwater management techniques that strive to restore or maintain the pre-development hydrograph.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 300
properties.hasText: Maintain biologically significant areas, including [[Peregrine Falcon]] nesting areas, reptile den sites, and significant salamander occurrences through active management of outcrops to reduce the intrusion by alder, rhododendron, and other species that contribute to the disappearance of some vertebrates.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 301
properties.hasText: Control invasive species and protect or restore areas already affected by invasive species to protect against changing climate conditions.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 302
properties.hasText: Use a hand crew to manually cut down encroaching woody vegetation with chainsaws or brush blades. Any use of herbicides and surfactants will need to be of low toxicity to wildlife.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 314
properties.hasText: Make efforts toretain old growth floodplain forest (e.g., for [[Chimney Swift]]s, bats, and herpetofauna).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 315
properties.hasText: Manage flow regimes in Coastal Plain rivers as much as possible to mirror the pre-dam hydrograph.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 326
properties.hasText: Protect these habitats through active management to remove invasive species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 327
properties.hasText: Burn around open, dry outcrops that naturally burned to restore more natural structure around the margins, and favor species that will tolerate drought and wildfire better.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 328
properties.hasText: Maintain biologically significant areas, including [[Peregrine Falcon]] nesting areas, reptile den sites, and significant salamander occurrences.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 329
properties.hasText: Assign appropriate management schemes to rock outcrops on conservation lands to minimize negative impacts from human activities, including recreational use and development.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 338
properties.hasText: Initiate a prescribed fire regime to prevent invasive plants and prevent habitat conversion.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 339
properties.hasText: Protect this habitat through active management to remove invasive species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 355
properties.hasText: Where possible, remove or exclude feral animals. Exclosure plots and electric fences should be considered as methods to prevent grazing or trampling (Porter et al. 2014).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 356
properties.hasText: Control the number of feral horses and contain populations of free roaming horses to reduce habitat damage (Porter et al. 2014).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 372
properties.hasText: Although protected by law in North Carolina, feral horse herds should be restricted from some areas where they currently roam free. Such restriction would be particularly beneficial at Shackleford Banks and Currictuck National Wildlife Refuge (Porter et al. 2014). Fence off portions of barrier islands where feral horses still occur to allow recovery of maritime grassland communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 373
properties.hasText: Where sand supply is abundant and substrate is appropriate, restore overwash processes that carry sand from the seaward to the landward side of an island and may allow landward migration and improve prospects for survival.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 374
properties.hasText: Collect seeds of the rarest plant species associated with maritime grasslands (especially annual species) to protect genetic diversity and maintain a source of local material that can be used to reestablish populations if species are extirpated or severely impacted within North Carolina.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 375
properties.hasText: Control predators (not limited to exotic species) through education efforts, trapping, or other means to increase sea turtle and beach-nesting bird reproductive success.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 376
properties.hasText: Make efforts to address beach lighting, sand fencing, sand pushing, and beach stabilization issues so that sea turtles have a better chance for nesting success.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 377
properties.hasText: Continue the use of bird decoys and sound broadcasts to attract colonial nesting birds to better nesting sites.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 378
properties.hasText: Continue coordination to influence where dredged material is placed to be most beneficial/least detrimental to beach-nesting birds, foraging shorebirds, and sea turtles.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 379
properties.hasText: Reduce disturbance from off-road vehicles, people, and their pets on coastal beach and dune systems. Continued support for and enhanced coordination among coastal management agencies regarding existing restrictions and programs aimed at regulating beach activities is also critical.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 388
properties.hasText: Maintain connections between habitatblocks, not only to allow adjustments in range in response to climate change, but to maintain population resilience and adaptability more generally.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 389
properties.hasText: Create transportation facilities that utilize longer bridges at streams and wetlands to minimize impacts (and thereby reduce mitigation requirements) and provide crossing options for wildlife that often travel riparian corridors and disperse to upland communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 390
properties.hasText: For protected and unprotected sites, control the exotic plants that are present or may potentially invade.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 401
properties.hasText: Maintain connections between habitat blocks, not only to allow adjustments in range in response to climate change, but to maintain population resilience and adaptability more generally.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 418
properties.hasText: Restore highly degraded stands; options include clear cutting and managing succession to control invasive species (i.e., ecological forestry).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 419
properties.hasText: Foster efforts to understand and implement appropriate management techniques (e.g., prescribed fire or thinning) for the benefit of the broadest array of oak forest-dependent wildlife, while taking into account specific needs of wildlife with more restrictive requirements (Artman and Downhower 2003; Ford et al. 2000).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 42
properties.hasText: Expand hatchery facilities to increase capacity for propagation of priority and nongame species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 420
properties.hasText: Manage the existing conservation lands, including the use of prescribed burning to diversify structure and composition of forest understory, and other silvicultural techniques to promote regeneration. This provides an array of age class and structural composition, and promotes long-term economic sustainability of montane oak forests.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 43
properties.hasText: Ensure that management of riverine habitats promotes the natural evolution and movement of woody and rocky structures and natural processes like bank dynamics, channel meanders, and flood regimes.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 434
properties.hasText: Reintroduction of fire to unconverted nonalluvial mineral wetland sites is the single most important factor to restore these sites.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 435
properties.hasText: Plowed firelines along transition zones between habitats should be rehabilitated (smoothed over) where possible. New firelines should be constructed when necessary. These areas should be maintained as a permanent narrow opening by discing with a tractor or by wetting with water or foam prior to a burn.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 436
properties.hasText: Control tide water penetration and saltwater intrusion with tide gates where feasible.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 437
properties.hasText: Where fire cannot be introduced back into the site for smoke management or other reasons, the use of a hydro-ax or other chipping machinery should be considered to control midstory.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 44
properties.hasText: Implement and support use of agriculture and forestry Best Management Practices (BMPs) to control stormwater runoff. Structures such as bioretention cells (i.e., rain gardens), cisterns, permeable pavement, runnels, vegetated swales, and filter strips can be used in various ways as stormwater BMPs.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 45
properties.hasText: Support fencing livestock out of streams as a measure to protect riparian vegetation, maintain bank stability, and reduce nutrient inputs to the aquatic system.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 451
properties.hasText: Consider and implement silvicultural management at appropriate locations to enhance understory development, provide regeneration and habitat for disturbance-dependent species or early successional species, such as [[Golden-winged Warbler]], and enhance mature forest conditions in young to middle-aged pure stands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 452
properties.hasText: Expand management of existing northern hardwood forests and adjacent habitats (particularly spruce–fir forests) to ensure the complete mix of age class, composition, and conditions necessary to sustain populations of a wide range of species that utilize this community.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 46
properties.hasText: Reduce impervious surfaces as one measure to control runoff and erosion. Research has shown that impervious levels of 8%–12% represent a threshold where small changes in urganization can cause major changes in stream condition (Wang et al. 2001). There are also many BMPs that may be alternatives to reduce runoff. Encourage use of pervious paving materials where feasible.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 463
properties.hasText: Create transportation facilities that utilize longer bridges at streams and wetlands to minimize impacts (and thereby reduce mitigation requirements) and provide crossing options for wildlife that often travel these riparian corridors and disperse to upland communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 464
properties.hasText: Work with adjacent states on mutual planning and conservation for regional species concerns, especially since some priority species are likely to expand their range due to climate change impacts.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 465
properties.hasText: Control invasive species in the short run, while populations are relatively limited and small, to prevent greater damage by them in the future.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 466
properties.hasText: Use infrequent prescribed fire and canopy gap management to improve forest structural heterogeneity (frequent fire will limit shrub and understory development necessary to breeding bird species).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 467
properties.hasText: Manage and protect mixed hardwoods/pine to promote future large, unfragmented tracts. This is especially important for amphibians, reptiles, small mammals, and bats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 468
properties.hasText: Target invasive and exotic species control at ecologically sensitive areas and at new and potentially manageable outbreaks.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 47
properties.hasText: Initiate a drought management program that modifies discharge permits when base flow conditions decrease and the 7Q10 is lowered.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 48
properties.hasText: Augment in-stream habitat to enhance its structural complexity to increase fish community abundance, biomass, and diversity (Hrodey and Sutton 2008).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 481
properties.hasText: Restore hydrology by reversing the effects of artificial drainage, as this is probably the most important action to protect pocosins.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 482
properties.hasText: Institute a prescribed fire regime, especially on conserved lands. Burning can often be accomplished on uplands without the use of fire-lines in transition zones between upland sites and pocosin habitats (especially in winter). This promotes a healthy transition zone between the two habitats that is critical for many plant species and allows for nutrient flow to some pocosin habitats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 49
properties.hasText: Preserve or restore riparian vegetation to maintain stable streambanks and dissipate water runoff energy, which allows for sediment deposition.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 495
properties.hasText: Maintain natural shoreline vegetation and the structure of adjacent terrestrial habitats if possible (many wetland-related amphibian and reptile species rely on both aquatic and drier upland sites for their life history and seasonal migrations).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 496
properties.hasText: Retain or create snags, logs, rocks, and other structures used by basking reptiles.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 497
properties.hasText: Reduce disturbance and development along raceways and near [[Bald Eagle]] nest trees.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 498
properties.hasText: Identify invasive and exotic species, their impacts on native wildlife, and practical methods for removal or control.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 499
properties.hasText: Plant native vegetation where appropriate to provide aquatic and terrestrial habitatand to reduce erosion and sedimentation.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 50
properties.hasText: In managed rivers, restore stream flows that promote controlled overbank flows and hydrological connectivity between the river and the floodplain.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 508
properties.hasText: Minimize the negative effects on beach ecology from beach renourishment projects by following a set of BMPs that include proper sediment choice, timing, spatial implementation, site-based design, ecological monitoring, and minimizing conflicts of interest

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 509
properties.hasText: Break large renourishment projects into smaller project zones in order to minimize impacts of direct burial to turtle nests. Intersperse project zones with untouched beach to facilitate recolonization of invertebrate fauna (Speybroeck et al. 2006).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 51
properties.hasText: Update flood maps as required by changes in flood patterns (frequency and duration) and flooded lands to ensure protection of life and property (Band and Salvesen 2009).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 510
properties.hasText: Complete renourishment projects before the start of the warm season to improve chances of invertebrate recolonization. Project implementation should be avoided at times that coincide with critical life stages of sensitive species, such as beach-nesting turtles or piping plover nesting seasons (Speybroeck et al. 2006).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 511
properties.hasText: Although protected by law in North Carolina, feral horse herds should be restricted from some areas where they currently roam free. Such restriction would be particularly beneficial at Shackleford Banks and Currituck National Wildlife Refuge (Porter et al. 2014). Use exclosures to fence off portions of barrier islands where feral horses still occur, allowing recovery of maritime grassland communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 519
properties.hasText: Seek opportunities to restore canebreak communities through controlled burning or other management strategies.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 52
properties.hasText: Protect potential migration corridors and preserve connectivity that allows for species and ecosystem migration.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 520
properties.hasText: Maintain large trees around reservoirs for potential eagle nests, and maintain forest cover in the tailrace below dams for eagle foraging.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 521
properties.hasText: Participate in mutual planning with adjacent states for regional species concerns, because some priority species are likely to expand their range due to climate change impacts.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 522
properties.hasText: Plant riparian areas with vegetation with a broad elevational range within a particular watershed. Also plant vegetation with broad hydrologic tolerance to promote resilience from climate change.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 526
properties.hasText: Maintain and restore connections between habitat blocks, not only to allow adjustments in range in response to climate change, but to maintain genetic connectivity, population resilience and adaptability more generally.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 527
properties.hasText: Transportation facilities that utilize longer bridges at streams and wetlands not only minimize impacts (and thereby reduce mitigation requirements) but also provide crossing options for wildlife that often travel riparian corridors. Wildlife underpasses should be constructed for all new highway projects, as these reduce wildlife-vehicle collisions, conserve important travel corridors, and provide linkages for bear populations and many other wildlife species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 528
properties.hasText: Limit the development of roads or other infrastructure within large unfragmented blocks, as this would promote the development of denser human settlement or create connectivity barriers through fragmentation.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 545
properties.hasText: Develop and/or implement techniques for managing pure spruce stands to include habitat components of the entire spruce–fir/northern hardwood community (i.e., thinning).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 546
properties.hasText: Test silvicultural techniques to reintroduce spruce into formerly disturbed areas that have regenerated in northern hardwood or Northern Red Oak communities (i.e., thinning and underplanting).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 547
properties.hasText: Protect spruce–fir communities from wildfire, as this is an important action that can be taken to save the remnants of these communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 561
properties.hasText: The best benefit for Coastal Plain riverine aquatic communities would be to maintain and enhance riparian buffers.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 562
properties.hasText: Determine the impacts of snagging (removing woody debris after storms) on wildlife populations.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 564
properties.hasText: Explore the biological controls recommended for some aquatic plants species, as they can be a problem, particularly in impounded waters and in slower moving waters.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 576
properties.hasText: Maintain and restore connections between habitat blocks, not only to allow adjustments in range in response to climate change, but to maintain genetic connectivity, population resilience, and adaptability more generally.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 577
properties.hasText: Develop transportation facilities that utilize longer bridges at streams and wetlands to minimize impacts (and thereby reduce mitigation requirements) and provide crossing options for wildlife that often travel riparian corridors. Wildlife underpasses should be constructed for all new highway projects, as these reduce wildlife–vehicle collisions, conserve important travel corridors, and provide linkages for bear populations and many other wildlife species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 580
properties.hasText: Allow Beaver pond complexes to develop in natural areas where direct impacts to rare species are not at issue.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 581
properties.hasText: Work with partners to develop property tax incentives to mitigate damages suffered by landowners.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 582
properties.hasText: Explore management strategies to eradicate undesirable species, such as bullfrogs, from wetlands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 583
properties.hasText: Maintain sufficient surrounding habitat for seasonal wetlands in order to support the life history requirements of amphibian and reptile populations. Every effort should be made to maintain continuous gradients between wetland and upland sites; roads, agriculture, or forestry operations between complimentary sites may render them ineffective at supporting amphibian and reptile populations (Bailey et al. 2004).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 598
properties.hasText: Employ hydrological restoration methods such as plugging ditches where ditches are affecting the hydrology of the pools.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 599
properties.hasText: Promote the adoption of agricultural and forestry best management practices (BMPs) that reduce run-off, erosion, and pollution. The federal Farm Bill and other cost share programs provide incentives for land stewards to adopt these practices.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 605
properties.hasText: Specific management needs include the control of woody encroachment and succession, the maintenance (and where necessary, restoration) of natural surface water and groundwater hydrology (using ditch plugs, temporary dams, level spreaders, or other engineering devices), the restoration of herbaceous vegetation, and the prohibition of take of rare bog-related species (e.g., Bog Turtle).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 612
properties.hasText: Establish examples of well-maintained and burned savannas as demonstration sites for landowners to emulate. Burning should be accomplished without placing firelines in transition zones from uplands to wetlands and with the fire allowed to burn through transition zones.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 613
properties.hasText: Habitat restoration should primarily occur through growing season prescribed burning, to develop and maintain the herbaceous layer and open pine stands. Where growing season burns cannot be administered, winter burns can be constructive. Burning should be accomplished without placing firelines in transition zones from uplands to wetlands and with the fire allowed to burn through transition zones.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 614
properties.hasText: Snags should be retained during logging operations to increase the numbers available for cavity-using wildlife species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 615
properties.hasText: Maintain sufficient levels of woody debris in stands for reptiles, amphibians, and small mammals.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 616
properties.hasText: Create borrow sites or ponds for breeding use by amphibians. Otherwise, amphibians are scarce in most flatwoods and savannas devoid of pools or open water.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 617
properties.hasText: Watch for arrival of Cogon Grass and other new invaders and control promptly.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 73
properties.hasText: Where feasible and cost effective, install gates to limit access (similar to protective measures used at Cranberry Mine). Inspection and monitoring may be needed to detect vandalism and illegal entry.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 74
properties.hasText: Identify ways to address the effects of WNS where it occurs in the state.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 87
properties.hasText: Increasethe effective connectivity (i.e., gene flow) between headwater brook trout populations through removal of artificial barriers and promote habitatconnectivity.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Management Practices Priority 92
properties.hasText: Reduce impervious surfaces as one measure to control runoff and erosion. Researchhas shown that impervious levels of 8%–12% represent a region where small changes in urbanization can cause major changes in stream condition (Wang et al. 2001). There are also many BMPs that may be alternatives to reduce runoff.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 100
properties.hasText: An integrated pest management strategy is needed; detection and monitoring of plant pest infestations needs to be an integral part of the strategy.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 101
properties.hasText: Investigate treatment options (e.g., foliar sprays, systemic soil treatments, aerial fungal pathogens, biological controls) and monitor applications to determine best method for stand-level treatments (Onken and Reardon 2005; MDA 2010).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 11
properties.hasText: Given the limited availability and number of threats facing mountain bog habitat, considerable effort needs to be expended to determine if populations are increasing, decreasing, or remaining stable.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 111
properties.hasText: Establish long-term monitoring efforts for small mammals and reptiles in the habitat. Monitoring protocols and procedures need to be developed or refined that will allow us to measure population trends of the priority wildlife species, as well as the health and distribution of this relatively rare habitat through time.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 112
properties.hasText: Enhance current monitoring systems and protocols (e.g., MAPS and BBS) to better cover species not well covered by current monitoring efforts.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 12
properties.hasText: Monitor amphibian populations to detect incidence of fungal and viral infections (e.g., iridoviruses, chytridiomycosis).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 121
properties.hasText: Develop monitoring for any North Carolina dry Longleaf Pine bird species that require specialized attention, since neither BBS nor standard point counts adequately sample for many species like [[Bachman's Sparrow]], Nightjars, [[American Kestrel]], [[Henslow's Sparrow]], and [[Red-headed Woodpecker]].

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 122
properties.hasText: Expand and/or target monitoring systems to be able to assess current population status and trend information for all wildlife species associated with dry Longleaf Pine habitats, in particular reptiles such as Northern Pinesnake, Southern Hognose Snake, and Coachwhip.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 13
properties.hasText: Monitor connectivity of populations separated by fragmentation.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 137
properties.hasText: Develop and maintain an integrated monitoring network to collect information for assessment of ecosystem outcomes and management actions associated with the implementation of management actions (APNEP 2012).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 138
properties.hasText: Facilitate the development of protocols and conduct rapid assessments to determine presence and potential threat of invasive species (APNEP 2012).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 139
properties.hasText: Develop sensors for biological and chemical sensing to determine status and trends, as well as tagging and tracking of wildlife (NIEPS 2010).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 14
properties.hasText: If Beaver activity is detected in nearby streams, monitor to detect problems from flooding or inundation.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 140
properties.hasText: Coordinate and enhance water quality, physical habitat,and fisheries resource monitoring (including data management) from headwaters to the nearshore ocean.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 161
properties.hasText: Continue monitoring beach-nesting birds due to their high vulnerability.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 162
properties.hasText: Begin monitoring potential changes to offspring sex ratios for species with temperature-dependent sex determination (all sea turtles, Diamondback Terrapins, American Alligators).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 163
properties.hasText: Collect spatial information on the distribution of estuarine habitats, document their characteristics, such as salinity, water levels, plant community struction and density, and monitor marsh die-back events.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 181
properties.hasText: Continue nest monitoring for colonial waterbirds, especially [[Wood Stork]]s.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 182
properties.hasText: Continue long-term monitoring of active [[Bald Eagle]] territories, successful breeding pairs, and fledged eagles.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 183
properties.hasText: Establish Monitoring Avian Productivity and Survivorship (MAPS) and migration banding stations, as well as specialized long-term monitoring for hard-to-sample species such as the Cerulean and Swainson's warbler (Graves 2001).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 185
properties.hasText: Investigate the past, current, and potential future impact of nutria on both floral and faunal communities and individual species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 188
properties.hasText: Determine the conservation and restoration efforts needed for priority species in this habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 192
properties.hasText: Make an attempt to protect waterbird nesting colonies.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 215
properties.hasText: Expand and/or target monitoring systems to be able to assess current population status and trend information for all wildlife species associated with floodplain forest habitats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 217
properties.hasText: Develop monitoring for any North Carolina floodplain forest bird species that require specialized attention, since neither BBS nor standard point counts can adequately sample irregularly distributed or clumped species like Kentucky, Cerulean, and Swainson's warblers.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 218
properties.hasText: Develop or enhance long-term monitoring for amphibians and reptiles (Taylor and Jones 2002).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 219
properties.hasText: Develop or enhance long-term monitoring for most bat species (Ellis et al. 2002).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 220
properties.hasText: Conduct long-term monitoring for floodplain forest birds (breeding, migration, and winter periods) in forest patches of varying size (Robbins et al. 1989; Doherty and Grubb 2000).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 221
properties.hasText: Establish long-term monitoring for herpetofauna using floodplain forest habitat (especially breeding salamanders and snakes).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 222
properties.hasText: Examine demographics and habitat use of bats in floodplain forests; there is also a need to identify, monitor, and maintain (or recruit) key bat habitats and microhabitats in floodplain forests (Ellis et al. 2002).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 272
properties.hasText: Begin long-term monitoring, following survey data, for all marshbirds, mammals, and reptiles in this habitat type.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 283
properties.hasText: Monitor priority small mammal and reptile population trends and habitat use.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 291
properties.hasText: Determine population trends and persistence of small wetland breeding amphibian populations, particularly the Mole Salamander, Eastern Tiger Salamander, Dwarf Salamander, and Four-toed Salamander.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 297
properties.hasText: Monitor endemic species closely for declines in the near future. Transplantation may be required to prevent extinction.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 298
properties.hasText: Continue monitoring the [[Peregrine Falcon]] population.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 299
properties.hasText: Monitor priority mammal and reptile population trends and habitat use.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 311
properties.hasText: Develop or enhance long-term monitoring for amphibians and reptiles (Taylor and Jones 2002). There is also a decided lack of long-term monitoring information on most bat species (Ellis et al. 2002).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 312
properties.hasText: Continue existing programs and expand monitoring of anoxic and hypoxic water conditions, particularly during spring anadromous fish spawning, summer droughts, and before and after tropical storms.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 313
properties.hasText: Install new and maintain existing USGS flow/water quality monitoring stations to collect real-time dischargeand DO data.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 325
properties.hasText: Continue monitoring Green Salamander populations, as well as other salamanders of this habitat type (e.g., Crevice and Southern Zigzag salamanders).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 34
properties.hasText: Monitor aquatic taxa to assess species and ecosystem health and to gauge resiliency of organisms to a changing climate.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 35
properties.hasText: Develop long-term monitoring strategies to document population trends, from which conservation strategies can be specifically designed to target those species which are experiencing declines.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 351
properties.hasText: Establish MAPS and migration banding stations in this habitat type.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 352
properties.hasText: Establish long-term monitoring of amphibians and reptiles, once survey data has been established.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 353
properties.hasText: Carefully monitor loss of this habitat from sea level rise.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 354
properties.hasText: Continue long-term monitoring and banding work (currently being done by the USGS) on Eastern [[Painted Bunting]]s and support the goals and objectives of the [[Painted Bunting]] Working Group that involves Florida, Georgia, South Carolina, and North Carolina.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 36
properties.hasText: Monitor population trends to determine if species are adapting to changing habitats and apply what is learned to future management decisions (Bakke 2008).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 367
properties.hasText: Continue support for regular colonial waterbird surveys (currently conducted coast-wide roughly every three years).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 368
properties.hasText: Continue sea turtle nest and stranding monitoring.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 369
properties.hasText: Monitor introduced nonnative species effects (especially plants and invertebrates) on native coastal wildlife, including sea turtles.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 37
properties.hasText: Use survey efforts to develop long-term monitoring strategies that will document population trends and provided a basis to design conservation strategies that target priority species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 370
properties.hasText: Monitor status and reproductive success of [[Gull-billed Tern]]s, [[Common Tern]]s, [[Least Tern]]s, [[Black Skimmer]]s, [[Piping Plover]]s, and [[Caspian Tern]]s.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 371
properties.hasText: Determine seasonal numbers and distribution of shorebirds (Dinsmore et al. 1998).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 38
properties.hasText: Monitor the effect of base flow impacts on priority species and correlate results with climate conditions.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 385
properties.hasText: Enhance current monitoring systems and protocols (e.g., MAPS and BBS) to better cover certain species not well covered by current monitoring efforts.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Monitoring Priority 386
