properties.hasText: In some areas of its range, the Longtail Salamander is associated with caves or portions of caves. Investigate its habitat use in North Carolina in conjunction with more generalized research on this species' distribution, status, and habitat in the state.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 68
properties.hasText: Conduct studies to document maternity sites used by bats from specific hibernacula (e.g., find maternity colonies utilizing radio telemetry of individual Virginia Big-eared Bats that hibernate in known caves/mines, or track any Indiana or Gray bats captured to their maternity sites or hibernacula).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 7
properties.hasText: Use clearing methods that create the least impacts; avoid use of chemicals. Where appropriate, use prescribed burning to control encroachment by hardwoods. If mowing, limit to once a year or less and set blade height between 1 and 2 feet to avoid destroying nesting bird and small mammal habitat.If using heavy equipment, disturb only one patch of the site at a time and minimize ruts and compaction of soils and vegetation to the extent possible (Somers et al. 2000).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 8
properties.hasText: If livestock grazing is allowed, limit number of animals to one per acre and allow light to moderate seasonal (winter only) grazing where possible (Somers et al. 2000).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 80
properties.hasText: Determine specific flow regimes necessary to support microhabitat for particular species (e.g., Junaluska Salamander).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 81
properties.hasText: Determine the effect that Beaver ponds have on downstream movement of toxins and sediment.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 82
properties.hasText: Gather better information regarding the inputs and influence of groundwater sources to accurately predict the influence of climate change on coldwater systems.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 83
properties.hasText: Conduct genetic research to resolve taxonomic issues for aquatic species, such as the Acuminate Crayfish' complex (Cambarus sp. C) and a Lake Waccamaw Lampsilis mussel complex.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 84
properties.hasText: Study the combined effect of land use changes and climatic effects on long-term stream temperature trends as they relate to native brook trout protection, restoration, and management.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 85
properties.hasText: Investigate thermal tolerance for brook trout and other native species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 9
properties.hasText: Provide native vegetation buffers around wetlands to filter pollutants and benefit wildlife (Somers et al. 2000).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Research Priority 98
properties.hasText: Conduct studies of bird, amphibian, reptile, and vegetation responses to gap management or specific timber harvest regimes (e.g., the [[Cerulean Warbler]], [[Swainson's Warbler]], [[Yellow-bellied Sapsucker]], and various reptiles and plethodontid salamanders).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 1
properties.hasText: For many of the priority species associated with mountain bogs, we do not have a clear understanding of their current distribution within the state. We must undertake surveys to gather baseline information on the distribution and status of most of these species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 107
properties.hasText: Determine the current baseline distribution and status of species mainly associated with dry coniferous forest (especially those that are state-listed or believed to be declining). Data is most severely lacking for reptiles, small mammals, and nocturnal birds.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 108
properties.hasText: Survey White Pine forest for breeding birds and other fauna. This habitat might now be utilized by species that formerly occurred in Canada Hemlock stands that have now shifted to White Pine habitats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 119
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys to document the distribution, relative abundance, and status of priority wildlife species associated with dry Longleaf Pine habitats.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 131
properties.hasText: Facilitate the mapping of significant ecological, bathymetric, geologic, demographic, and cultural features (APNEP 2012).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 132
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys of fish populations, including collecting fish samples for toxicological and water quality studies, to evaluate the efficacy of management practices, detect changes in fish communities, and to identify trends which may be occurring within the fishery resources.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 155
properties.hasText: Gather baseline information on sex ratios for species with temperature-dependent sex determination (all sea turtles, terrapins, alligators) to characterize impacts from climate change.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 176
properties.hasText: Document [[Bald Eagle]] nesting sites.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 177
properties.hasText: Survey for poorly known or secretive semi-aquatic snakes—Rainbow Snake, Glossy Crayfish Snake, and Black Swamp Snake.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 178
properties.hasText: Determine the breeding and roosting status and distribution of [[Chimney Swift]]s in natural conditions along major floodplains with appropriate habitat conditions (e.g. older, hollow trees).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 179
properties.hasText: Design specific surveys to determine status and distribution of birds not adequately picked up by the Breeding Bird Survey in floodplain forests (e.g., the [[Cerulean Warbler]], [[Swainson's Warbler]], [[Kentucky Warbler]], [[Worm-eating Warbler]], [[Hooded Warbler]], [[Prothonotary Warbler]], etc.).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 18
properties.hasText: Conduct stream surveys adjacent to areas poised for development (edge of urban expansion) to establish baseline populations and identify problems before development expands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 180
properties.hasText: Survey for bat species that roost or forage in blackwater systems.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 19
properties.hasText: Work cooperatively with partners to collect occurrence and abundance data on macrobenthic species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 196
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys to document the distribution, relative abundance, and status of wildlife species associated with brownwater floodplain forest habitats. Priorities include [[Swallow-tailed Kite]], [[Cerulean Warbler]], [[Wood Stork]], bats, and species believed to be declining, at risk, or mainly dependent on floodplain forest communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 197
properties.hasText: Give secondary priority to surveys of species for which current distribution information is already available or for species that are considered common.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 199
properties.hasText: Determine the status and distribution of Wayne's [[Black-throated Green Warbler]].

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 20
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys to detect presence and collect life-history and abundance data for freshwater snails and crayfishes, as there is limited information available on these species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 200
properties.hasText: Determine the status and distribution of the [[Swallow-tailed Kite]], [[Mississippi Kite]], Yellow-crowned Night-heron, and [[Anhinga]] (as well as other colonial nesting waterbirds).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 201
properties.hasText: Determine the breeding and roosting status and distribution of the [[Chimney Swift]] in natural conditions along major floodplains with appropriate habitat conditions (e.g., older, hollow trees).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 202
properties.hasText: Determine the status and distribution of priority bat species, including Northern Long-eared Bat, Rafinesque's Big-eared Bat, Northern Yellow Bat, Seminole Bat, Southeastern Bat, Little Brown Bat, and Tricolored Bat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 203
properties.hasText: Conduct small mammal surveys, especially for the Eastern Woodrat, with a focus on circumneutral soils (other small mammal survey needs include the Cotton Mouse and Southern Pygmy Shrew).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 204
properties.hasText: Determine the status and distribution of snakes using floodplain forest habitats (Taylor and Jones 2002).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 279
properties.hasText: Obtain baseline data on high-elevation bird species of grassy and heath balds, especially [[Golden Eagle]], [[Vesper Sparrow]], and [[Alder Flycatcher]].

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 280
properties.hasText: Obtain baseline data on mammal and reptile communities and habitat use (e.g., identify Timber Rattlesnake den sites).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 287
properties.hasText: Initiate distribution surveys for all amphibian species associated with headwater communities, but especially the Mole Salamander, Eastern Tiger Salamander, Dwarf Salamander, and Four-toed Salamander.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 288
properties.hasText: Gather better information about the status and distribution of more common species associated with [[Piedmont]] headwater and associated wetland habitats (e.g., Three-lined Salamander, Common Ribbonsnake).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 293
properties.hasText: Survey for new [[Peregrine Falcon]] nests.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 294
properties.hasText: Obtain baseline data on small mammal communities and reptile communities and habitat use (e.g., identify Timber Rattlesnake den sites).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 306
properties.hasText: Carry out surveys todocument the distribution, relative abundance, and status of many wildlife species associated with riverine habitats. Priorities for conducting surveys need to focus on species believed to be declining, at risk, or mainly dependent on riverine communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 307
properties.hasText: Conduct additional surveys for species for which current distribution information is already available or for species that are considered common (NCWRC 2005).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 318
properties.hasText: Map these sites in a GIS format to facilitate tracking changes over time in both the habitat and the associated species, and to facilitate landscape scale management of this rare habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 319
properties.hasText: Obtain baseline data on amphibian, small mammal, and reptile communities and habitat use (e.g., identify Timber Rattlesnake den sites).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 332
properties.hasText: Determine the effects of current drought conditions on vegetated communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 333
properties.hasText: Map these sites in a GIS format to facilitate tracking changes over time in the habitat, as well as the associated species and facilitate landscape scale management of this rare habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 334
properties.hasText: Conduct detailed surveys, such as moth trapping, at Buck Creek Barrens, the largest mafic barrens site in the state.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 335
properties.hasText: Monitor drought conditions and potential for catastrophic wildfire.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 342
properties.hasText: Determine the status and distribution of amphibians and reptiles in maritime communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 343
properties.hasText: Conduct migration surveys to determine bird use, especially during the fall.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 344
properties.hasText: Conduct small mammal surveys on barrier island systems to verify species status, distribution, and community composition.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 359
properties.hasText: Surveys are needed to document the distribution, relative abundance and status of wildlife species associated with these beach/dune habitats. Priorities for conducting surveys need to focus on species believed to be declining, at risk, or mainly dependent on these communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 360
properties.hasText: Secondary priority for surveys should be for species for which current distribution information is already available or for species that are considered common.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 361
properties.hasText: Conduct shorebird surveys throughout the year to better understand population fluctuations for breeding, wintering, and migratory birds (especially [[Piping Plover]], [[American Oystercatcher]], and [[Wilson's Plover]]).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 362
properties.hasText: Determine distribution and status of wintering shorebirds (Sprandel et al. 2000).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 382
properties.hasText: Direct initial efforts toward surveys to determine the current baseline distribution and status of species mainly associated with mesic forests (especially those that are state-listed or believed to be declining) for which that information is lacking.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 383
properties.hasText: Focus secondary efforts on conducting surveys to understand current status, from which we can measure future population changes over time.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 407
properties.hasText: Give priority to gathering baseline information regarding the current distribution and status of oak forest-associated species that are rare or declining (e.g., [[Black-capped Chickadee]], Eastern Fox Squirrel, Wehrle's Salamander, Timber Rattlesnake, and several bat species).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 408
properties.hasText: Expand surveys to include species for which we know very little about current status and distribution (e.g., Whip-poor-will, weasels, moles, shrews, bats, certain salamanders, and reptile species such as the Eastern Box Turtle).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 424
properties.hasText: Determine the status of Yellow-crowned Night-heron, other colonial nesting birds, Wayne's [[Black-throated Green Warbler]], as well as other neotropical migrants that are not well sampled by BBS.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 425
properties.hasText: Document the status and distribution of priority bat species (e.g. Rafinesque's Big-eared Bat, Northern Yellow Bat, Seminole Bat, Southeastern Bat, and Northern Long-eared Bat) in this habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 426
properties.hasText: Conduct Eastern Woodrat surveys and subsequently establish standardized long-term monitoring of the species in this habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 427
properties.hasText: Determine the status and distribution of Timber (Canebrake) and Pigmy rattlesnakes.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 428
properties.hasText: Survey for other SGCN and high priority species, especially snakes and lizards.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 440
properties.hasText: Fill in distribution gaps for Carolina Northern Flying Squirrel. Continue survey work on distributions within and between known populations.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 441
properties.hasText: Obtain baseline data on SGCN and priority species, especially species that depend on high-elevation forests.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 442
properties.hasText: Conduct shrew surveys to determine the distribution of Long-tailed, Pygmy, and Water shrews and surveys to document the response of shrews to disturbance/management.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 443
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys for rare salamanders like Weller's, Northern and Southern Pygmy, Seepage, and Tellico, as well as more common species such as Ravine Salamanders, to determine their actual distribution and better define their habitat associations.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 456
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys to document priority and common species in areas poised for development (edge of urban expansion) to establish baseline populations and identify problems before development expands.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 457
properties.hasText: Determine the current baseline distribution and status of species mainly associated with oak and mixed hardwood/pine forests (especially those that are state-listed or believed to be declining) for which that information is lacking.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 475
properties.hasText: Determine status and distribution for Wayne's [[Black-throated Green Warbler]], Worm-eating warbler, [[Swainson's Warbler]], [[Black-billed Cuckoo]] (may warrant further documentation), and other neotropical migrants.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 486
properties.hasText: Determine the status and distribution of reservoir-associated birds (e.g., ospreys, herons, swallows, possibly rails) and help identify threats to populations.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 487
properties.hasText: Survey for shorebird migration activity on large reservoirs (e.g., Falls Lake, Kerr Lake) in spring, summer and fall.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 488
properties.hasText: Conduct frog call surveys and support the volunteer and citizen science programs that participate in these surveys.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 503
properties.hasText: Conduct distributional and status surveys for pelagic and shore birds, small mammals, and reptiles that may utilize this habitat.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 512
properties.hasText: Determine the distribution and abundance of aquatic species, especially the Gulf Coast Spiny Softshell, Striped Mud Turtle, and Eastern Mudsnake.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 513
properties.hasText: Gather better information about the status and distribution of common species associated with riverine habitats (e.g., Three-lined Salamander, Common Ribbonsnake).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 514
properties.hasText: Expand research, survey, and monitoring efforts beyond collecting presence–absence data, to look at long-term trends across species groups, habitats, and the effects of management actions.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 523
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys for species for which current distribution information is already available or for species that are considered common or invasive (e.g., Gray Fox, Raccoon, Coyote).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 524
properties.hasText: Develop long-term monitoring strategies to document population trends, from which conservation strategies can be specifically designed to target those species (e.g., Coyote).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 534
properties.hasText: Determine the distribution, relative abundance, and status of all wildlife species associated with spruce–fir forests.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 535
properties.hasText: Focus survey priorities on species believed to be declining, at risk, or exclusively dependent on spruce–fir forest communities (e.g., the [[Red Crossbill]], [[Brown Creeper]], [[Black-capped Chickadee]], Rock Vole, Rock Shrew, Carolina Northern Flying Squirrel, Weller's Salamander, Northern and Southern Pigmy Salamanders, etc.).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 536
properties.hasText: Collect baseline microhabitat and microclimate characteristics in spruce–fir salamander communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 550
properties.hasText: Determine the components of foraging bat communities along rivers.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 551
properties.hasText: Establish species-specific surveys to improve our knowledge of the status and distribution of the [[Least Bittern]], [[American Bittern]], [[Yellow Rail]], and [[Black Rail]] at all times of the year (Conway et al. 2004).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 565
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys for species associated with successional habitats, including species for which current distribution information is already available or for species that are considered common (e.g., [[Eastern Meadowlark]], [[Blue Grosbeak]], Eastern Cottontail).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 566
properties.hasText: Continue surveys for all amphibian species associated with small wetland communities, but especially the Mole Salamander, Eastern Tiger Salamander, Dwarf Salamander, and Four-toed Salamander.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 567
properties.hasText: Gather better information about the status and distribution of more common species associated with [[Piedmont]] wetland habitats (e.g., the Three-lined Salamander, Common Ribbonsnake).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 590
properties.hasText: Investigate the status and distribution of species associated with [[Piedmont]] wetland habitats (e.g., Three-lined Salamander, Common Ribbonsnake).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 591
properties.hasText: Survey for all amphibian species associated with small wetland communities.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 607
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys to detect presence and collect life history and abundance data for freshwater snails and crayfish, as there is limited information available on these species.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 62
properties.hasText: Create a comprehensive, prioritized list of significant caves, including the factors which add significance (e.g., roost of endangered bats, rare geologic formations, other rare plants or animal use).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 63
properties.hasText: Survey for potential nesting birds in caves such as [[Turkey Vulture]]s, [[Black Vulture]]s, and [[Common Raven]]s.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 64
properties.hasText: Inventory salamander communities associated with cave habitat (particularly in the twilight zone of caves).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 65
properties.hasText: Conduct bat surveys in caves and mines that have not been previously evaluated.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 66
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys for Cave Salamanders (Eurycea lucifuga) in areas along the Tennessee/ North Carolina border.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 77
properties.hasText: Conduct baseline surveys to determine current distributions for the several SGCN associated with stream habitats in western North Carolina that are known in only a few localities, and/or are considered rare or declining (e.g., Water Shrew, Hellbender, Junaluska and Longtail Salamanders, Mudpuppy, Eastern Spiny Softshell, and Loggerhead Musk Turtles).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 78
properties.hasText: Gather better information about the status and distribution of more common species associated with stream habitats (e.g., Shovel-nosed and Three-linedSalamanders).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 79
properties.hasText: Investigate population status of native Brook Trout.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 89
properties.hasText: Distributional and status surveys are needed for aquatic snails, crayfish, mussels, and fish (in order of general need).

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 95
properties.hasText: Direct initial efforts toward surveys to determine current baseline distribution and status of species associated with cove hardwood forest for which that information is lacking.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 96
properties.hasText: Focus initial survey efforts on state-listed species and others that may be declining,such as the [[Cooper's Hawk]], [[Sharp-shinned Hawk]], [[Brown Creeper]], [[Black-billed Cuckoo]], [[Cerulean Warbler]], [[Yellow-bellied Sapsucker]], Green Salamander, Seepage Salamander, Pigmy Salamanders, Tellico Salamander, and Southern Zigzag Salamander.

properties.name: NCWAP 2015 Surveys Priority 97
properties.hasText: Conduct surveys to understand current status of species believed to be more common, from which we can measure future population changes (e.g., the [[Swainson's Warbler]], Silver-haired Bat, Long-tailed Weasel, Woodland Jumping Mouse, Eastern Mole, Smoky Shrew, Masked Shrew, Spotted Salamander, Marbled Salamander, Ravine Salamander, Eastern Hognose Snake, Eastern Box Turtle, and Eastern Smooth Earth Snake).
